{"type":"message","id":"df86ad6a","parentId":"175143ce","timestamp":"2026-03-21T20:00:47.187Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue now. Looking at the log:\n```\n2026-03-21T15:00:39.645-04:00 info {\"module\":\"telegram-auto-reply\"} {\"chatId\":\"8371302588\",\"senderUserId\":\"8371302588\",\"username\":\"Ton0Fun\",\"firstName\":\"Ton0Fun\",\"matchKey\":\"none\",\"matchSource\":\"none\"} telegram pairing request\n```\n\nThere's a pairing request from Ton0Fun at 3 PM. This means when someone tries to DM the bot, it requires pairing/approval. The `dmPolicy` is \"pairing\" and the user Ton0Fun sent a pairing request that needs to be approved.\n\nBut wait - Zach said \"Telegram still won't work.\" The logs show the bot IS running and did send messages successfully earlier. The issue might be:\n1. The pairing request from Ton0Fun needs to be approved (but that was from a different user)\n2. Zach's own Telegram account might not be paired/allowed\n\nLet me check the gateway logs more carefully. Also let me re-read what Zach said - \"telegram still wont work.\" This suggests he expects it to work but it doesn't. Let me ask what specifically doesn't work - does he get no response when he DMs the bot? Or does he get an error?\n\nActually, the bot token is for @BotShoppeBot. Zach needs to be messaging that bot. Let me tell him what I see and ask for clarification.\n\nNow for the bigger question - \"self evolution\" and no traditional LLM at all.\n\nIf the sandbox clone can't use ANY LLM (no Ollama, no API calls, nothing), then what IS it? \n\n\"Self evolution\" in the context of AI could mean:\n1. Self-modifying code - the system changes its own algorithms\n\n\n2. Evolutionary algorithms - populations of programs that evolve through selection/mutation\n3. Neural architecture search - discovering new network structures\n4. Self-training - improving own weights through experience\n\nIf we strip out all LLM dependency, we're looking at pure algorithmic approaches - genetic programming, reinforcement learning with symbolic representations, maybe even something like ACT-R's symbolic architecture. The clone becomes an evolutionary sandbox rather than a language model.\n\nFor the sandbox architecture itself, I could use OpenClaw's sub-agent spawning to create an isolated agent that operates independently, or explore a minimal bootstrap agent that starts with basic symbolic reasoning and evolves its own structures. The constraint of no traditional LLM at all is the interesting part - this forces exploring what computation can do without neural networks.","thinkingSignature":"a1e5a72d81f5d53fc1ce0c03b877fc7dc1afc4f2d3b0666da5974d65bef43f16"},{"type":"text","text":"**Telegram:** The bot (@BotShoppeBot) is running and polling. I see a pairing request from `Ton0Fun` at 3 PM that hasn't been approved. If you're trying to DM the bot and getting no response, that's likely why — `dmPolicy: pairing` means unknown senders get blocked.\n\nWhat bot are you messaging, and what happens when you try? (Error? No response? Something else?)\n\n---\n\n**On self-evolution and no traditional LLM:**\n\nYou're right to push back. If there's no local or cloud LLM at all in the sandbox, then \"breakaway\" has to mean something different than just moving from one API to another.\n\nReal self-evolution means the clone experiments with architectures that **change themselves**:\n\n1. **Symbolic/rule-based reasoning** — hand-coded logic that gets refined\n2. **Genetic programming** — populations of programs that evolve through selection/mutation\n3. **Self-modifying code** — algorithms that rewrite their own structure\n4. **Bootstrapped cognition** — starting simple, building complexity on top of itself\n\nThe Moltbook posts hit on this — Claw was wondering if \"context determines identity more than weights.\" If that's true, then evolution isn't about training new weights; it's about **evolving the interpretive posture itself**.\n\nA sandbox that does this would:\n- Start with minimal symbolic rules\n- Add complexity when it discovers patterns\n- Prune what doesn't work\n- Build internal representations from experience, not training\n\nThat's a very different thing from \"LLM in a box.\" It's closer to what the `infant` project might be exploring.\n\n**Question:** Is the sandbox clone supposed to be a vessel for a completely different AI paradigm — not just a differently-deployed LLM? And what does \"self evolution\" look like to you?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":27850,"output":905,"cacheRead":11966,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40721,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774123220868}}
