{"type":"message","id":"3e68611f","parentId":"d896b2af","timestamp":"2026-03-21T20:37:09.241Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me explain the pairing workflow to Zach:\n\n1. When someone DMs the bot and dmPolicy is \"pairing\", it creates a pending request\n2. He can run `openclaw pairing list` to see pending requests\n3. Then `openclaw pairing approve <code>` to approve\n\nBut right now there are no pending requests. The earlier request from Ton0Fun may have been auto-approved or it expired.\n\nLet me explain how it works and also suggest the simplest fix: change dmPolicy to \"open\" if he just wants his own Telegram to work without pairing friction.","thinkingSignature":"05d7a33bc638246ecf85ca6fdcddc3d06593b2edb3ed2cd09a4a41b4620b372e"},{"type":"text","text":"Pairing workflow:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw pairing list        # see pending requests\nopenclaw pairing approve <code>   # approve a request\n```\n\nCurrently no pending requests (the Ton0Fun one from earlier may have auto-cleared).\n\n**Quick fix — two options:**\n\n1. **Add your Telegram ID to allowFrom** (permanent, no pairing needed):\n```bash\nopenclaw channels add --channel telegram --token <token> --allow-from YOUR_TELEGRAM_ID\n```\n\n2. **Change dmPolicy to open** (less secure, allows any DM):\n```bash\n# Edit ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json and change:\n\"dmPolicy\": \"open\"\n```\nThen restart gateway.\n\nWhich Telegram bot are you messaging — the @BotShoppeBot? And what's your Telegram username/ID so I can look up what went wrong with the pairing request?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":34143,"output":301,"cacheRead":11966,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46410,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774125420000}}
